&lt;p&gt;The main culprit is the ConsumerChannelRegistry which uses a ThreadLocal variable to store a channel associated with the current transaction.  The registry does not use the ConnectionFactory as a key.  And since the receive channel is already registered in the registry, my messages end up getting sent through the receiving channel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Essentially what ends up happening is that even though I provide a different ConnectionFactory, the ConnectionFactoryUtils avoid creating a new channel because one already exists in the ConsumerChannelRegistry.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
